SIMPLE: principality
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Principality
<hw>Prin`ci*pal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Principalities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>principalitas</ets> pre⟦eum⟧minence, excellence: cf. F.
<ets>principalit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, <ets>principaut⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See
<er>Principal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Sovereignty; supreme power;
hence, superiority; predominance; high, or the highest, station.</def>
<rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>principalities</qex> shall come down, even the crown of
your glory.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xiii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prerogative and <qex>principality</qex> above everything
else.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A prince; one invested with sovereignty.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Next upstood Nisroch, of <xex>principalities</xex> the
prime.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The territory or jurisdiction of a prince; or the
country which gives title to a prince; <as>as, the <ex>principality</ex>
of Wales</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Principally</ent>⟦br⟧
